<H3> <TI>   Linked Domestic, Foreign Rice Sales Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503114094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1112 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0503114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 5 KYODO -- The Food Agency is to order 
wholesalers and retailers to stop tie-in sales of domestic and 
foreign rice next week, saying such practices go against the 
Antimonopoly Law, agency officials said Saturday [5 March]. 
  "Such practices deprive consumers from freedom to choose," 
an 
official at the agency said. 
  In the face of a shortfall in last year's rice crop because 
of the cool and rainy summer, Japan early this year began to 
sell foreign rice imported from Thailand and China either mixed 
with domestic rice or separately. 
  But some retailers and wholesalers are requiring customers 
to 
buy domestic and foreign rice as a set, since long-grain rice 
imported from Thailand is unpopular with Japanese consumers, who 
favor medium and short-grain rice as a food staple. 

</TEXT>

