<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Aid Mobile Communications Stations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503073594 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0503073594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A Post and Telecommunications Ministry source 
disclosed on 3 March that the government is planning to give 
financial support to the Japan Mobile Communications (IDO) to 
help it invest in plant and equipment as part of an expansion of 
base stations. The government has decided that the Japan 
Development Bank [JDB] can increase its loans to IDO for this 
project. As there are signs that progress will be made at 
Japan-U.S. negotiations, the government wants to help bring the 
negotiations to a successful conclusion and believes that 
supporting plans to increase the number of base stations will 
help. 
  Increasing the number of base stations for the Motorola 
cellular phone system became a focal point of Japan-U.S. 
negotiations on mobile and car telephones and the IDO submitted 
a compromise proposal designed to front-load the expansion plan. 
The JDB awarded the IDO loans amounting to 17 billion yen in 
fiscal 1992 and 25 billion yen in fiscal 1993. Under current 
regulations the loans can cover a maximum of only 50 percent of 
the investment total. The government, however, is trying to 
increase this about 70 percent. If it fails to achieve this, it 
will provide full support for loans to be provided at the 50 
percent level. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

