<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Planned Visit of U.S. Secretary of State Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903121294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0903121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Secretary of State Christopher will visit 
Japan for three days from 9 to 11 March. Taking advantage of 
his visit, the Japanese Government plans to seek ways to resume 
the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, which remain suspended, 
and to seek an understanding with the United States about 
Japan's efforts to open its market by explaining these efforts 
to Christopher. 
  He will be the first U.S. cabinet member to visit Japan 
since 
the Super 301 provision of the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act was 
revived. Christopher will meet separately with Prime Minister 
Hosokawa and Foreign Minister Hata and will deliver a speech to 
the opening ceremony of the "International Committee on the 
Reconstruction of Cambodia" to be held 10-11 March in Japan. He 
will also attend the first Japan-U.S. security consultations 
(the so-called 2-Plus-2 talks) to be held on 11 March in Tokyo, 
with senior foreign and defense officials from the two countries 
attending. U.S. Under Secretary of State Joan Spero, who is in 
charge of economic affairs and who arrived in Japan on 8 March 
prior to Christopher's visit, will meet with Deputy Foreign 
Minister Matsuura on the morning of 9 March. 
  At separate meetings with Secretary of State Christopher, 
Prime Minister Hosokawa and his cabinet ministers will brief him 
on a new package of economic stimulus measures, as well as 
Japan's measures to open its market, measures which the 
government plans to map out by the end of March. They will also 
seek his understanding of Japanese plans to create an 
environment for reducing its current account surplus through a 
steady expansion of domestic demand. In addition, they will 
consult with him on a set of compromise proposals by the 
Japanese private sector for settling bilateral negotiations on 
such sectors as cellular phones, automobiles, and semiconductors. 
  During the separate meetings, they will ask that the United 
States cautiously deal with the revived Super 301 provision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

