<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Notes Signs of Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203123394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0203123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a news conference following a cabinet meeting on 
1 March, International Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi 
Kumagai commented on the state of the economy, saying: "There 
are signs that the economy has been improving since the 
beginning of the year." In this way, he indicated that the 
economy had gone through the worst period. In January, 
industrial production and shipping indexes increased and an 
inventory-shipment ratio declined. Referring to this, Kumagai 
noted that there were signs of recovery in consumer spending and 
other areas. He said: "Although the sales of high-priced 
products are still sluggish, they are gradually picking up." 
  Concerning the imports of U.S. autos and auto parts 
discussed 
in the Japanese-U.S. framework trade talks, Kumagai said: "It 
is necessary for the Japanese industry to have a correct 
understanding of what the United States is thinking." 

</TEXT>

