<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   9 Mar N-S Contact Fails `To Make Any Progress' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0903061394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0603 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0903061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Panmunjom, Korea, March 9 (YONHAP) -- North and 
South Korea failed to make any progress on exchanging special 
envoys at a meeting in the truce village of Panmunjom on 
Wednesday, agreeing only to meet again this weekend. 
  At the meeting held in North Korea's Unification House, the 
South asked the North to drop four demands made at the previous 
four meetings and to respond to Seoul's proposal on an exchange 
of special envoys. 
  Vice Unification Minister Song Yong-tae, who led the South 
Korean delegation to the meeting, warned that if North Korea 
insisted on its "unreasonable demands," it would be accused of 
"erecting a barrier to a special envoy exchange." 
  Stressing that the envoy exchange is a pressing issue that 
cannot be put aside, he said he expects North and South Korea 
will jointly work for reconciliation, cooperation and 
co-prosperity by realizing an exchange of special envoys. 
  But chief North Korean delegate Pak Yong-su, reiterating the 
four demands, offered a counterproposal calling for two 
additional items, including maintenance of national 
self-reliance, in the agenda for discussion by the special 
envoys. He also proposed that the South Korean envoy visit 
Pyongyang first for three nights and four days and that the 
preparatory period for the visit be 15 days. 
  North Korea's four demands include suspension of the joint 
South Korea-U.S. military exercise "Team Spirit," withdrawal of 
President Kim Yong-sam's remarks on North Korea's nuclear 
program and scrapping of the U.S. plan to deploy Patriot 
missiles in South Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

