<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK, Russia To Open Research Complexes in Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0903120994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0154 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0903120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 9 (YONHAP) -- The Science and 
Technology Ministry has publicly invited South Korean research 
institutes and universities to take part in joint-venture 
research complexes in Russia with Russian think tanks and 
businesses this month. Ministry officials said Wednesday that 
Korea and Russia have decided to open three to four pilot 
research complexes in Moscow this year to accelerate transfers 
of advanced Russian technology. The project is expected to 
enhance current Korean-Russian research cooperation, exchanges 
of researchers and training of engineers, the officials said. 
  Through the program, Korea will be able to utilize Russia's 
vast and sophisticated research facilities and brainpower to 
acquire intensive scientific and technological information from 
the ex-superpower, they said. The complexes will be locally 
incorporated through joint investments, with Korea paying cash 
for maintenance and research in the beginning stage and Russia 
providing the facilities and manpower. Research will be focused 
on technologies concerning machinery, materials, and 
electric/electronics that are lacking among Korean manufacturers 
as well as physics, chemistry and other basic sciences. For its 
part, the government will offer advice, help in choosing, 
commissioning and registering Russian partners, and subsidies 
for research projects and other expenses, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

