<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Board of Audit Uncovers Cases of Budget Waste </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0903123094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1142 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0903123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Mar. 9 (YONHAP) -- The Board of Audit and 
Inspection [BAI] said on Wednesday it had uncovered 47 cases of 
budgetary waste among public offices. The board demanded 
disciplinary actions or warning against the public officials 
involved. A board official said his board made a budgetary 
inspection of the Economic Planning Board and 59 other 
government offices for five days beginning last Dec. 20. 
  "The check showed a number of offices squandered unused 
budgets in the year-end period or used them for purposes other 
than they were intended for," he said. The Health and Social 
Affairs Ministry, for instance, obtained 174 million won for use 
in distoma programs reasoning the money was needed in treating 
distoma patients, the number of whom it estimated at 50,000 in 
1993. The Ministry gave the estimate despite the fact that those 
stricken by distoma numbered no more than 7,900 to 14,000 a year 
in the 1990-92 period. The ministry used only 31 million won in 
distoma programs and diverted the remaining 143 million won to 
other purposes such as staffs' welfare programs. 
  In another incident, the Pusan police agency wasted 30 
million won by purchasing additional color films although there 
was a sufficient stock of them, he said. The official said 
unused budgetary funds were believed to reach 1189.6 billion won 
in 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

