<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Praised for Lifting Security Charge </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0803140194 Phnom Penh CAMBODIA TIMES in English 6-12 Mar 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK0803140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh CAMBODIA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "No Charge"] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Royal Government's decision to remove the 
security charge levied on local and foreign companies for the 
establishment of trade companies and foreign representative 
offices here, is a very welcome move. This will give Cambodia an 
edge in boosting foreign investments, especially in view of the 
fact that the United States embargo on Vietnam has finally been 
lifted. 
  No doubt there will be an expected clamour to invest in the 
Indochina region, but the country with the most pull will be the 
one which provides the best economic returns for the amount 
invested. And Cambodia cannot afford to be seen as lackadaisical 
about foreign investment, as the country needs foreign capital 
to rebuild the country. 
  It would be a pity to give up on this opportunity to attract 
investment, merely because the government did not act fast 
enough. Prior to this move, trading companies and foreign 
representative offices had to deposit U.S. $3,000 with the 
National Bank as caution money. [passage omitted] Cambodia has a 
lot to offer investors but more steps need to be taken to make 
life easier for them. If this means cutting down on a lot of 
red tape, then so be it. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

