<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Views U.S.-Japan Trade War, Super 301 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0903052694 Quezon City Radio Filipinas in English 0230 GMT 
9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0903052694 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Secretary Roberto Romulo says the trade war 
between the United States and Japan will adversely affect the 
economic recovery program of the Philippines. Interviewed by 
reporters in Manila, Secretary Romulo said the trade war between 
Japan and the United States will likely push Washington to 
reconsider its focus on the Asia-Pacific region. Romulo 
believes that because of its trade rift with Japan, America 
might favor the other regions, like Europe. Last week 
Washington reinstated one of its toughest trade laws, the law 
Super 301 allows U.S. President Bill Clinton to impose punitive 
tariffs of up to 100 percent on a country that obstructs import 
of U.S. products, but Secretary Romulo said he does not believe 
Super 301 will be slapped against the Philippines. The 
Philippines had been placed under the priority watch list of 
trade violators in the past but was delisted after addressing 
U.S. concern. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

