<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Block Products at `Dumping Prices' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0903084194 Manila MANILA BULLETIN in English 7 Mar 94 p B-1 </F>
<F P=103> BK0903084194 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Department of Trade and Industry has served 
notice that the government will counter attempts to hurt local 
manufacturers if foreign suppliers ship products to the 
Philippines at dumping prices. The mechanism to stop an import 
surge, according to Trade Secretary Rizalino S. Navarro, will be 
activated whenever unscrupulous suppliers injure local producers 
with shipments of competing products at artificially low prices. 
"While we are removing or liberalizing trade, you have to make 
sure the guy on the other shore does not prejudice industries 
here through unfair trade practices," he said. 
  Meanwhile, Navarro said, the import ban he proposed to the 
Monetary Board, policy body at the Central Bank of the 
Philippines late in February 1994 should not be treated as a 
signal that government was going back on its word to force local 
industries to be efficient by making it compete with foreign 
competitors. 
  "I am not going to open that door wider so that everybody is 
protected," he said, dousing cold water on speculations of local 
manufacturers on a government aboutface on its import 
liberalization program. The proposed ban was for a six-month 
period. It will apply on tires, refractory bricks, paper 
products, and glass products. Navarro recommended the temporary 
ban after monitoring showed a surge in imports on these four 
items. 
  Earlier, Sen. Leticia Ramos-Shahani asked the Senate to 
inquire into the reported dumping of foreign articles in the 
country at prices less than their fair market value in 
anticipation of the effectivity of the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade (GATT). The Philippines is a signatory to the 
GATT whose protocol would be submitted to the Senate for 
ratification. The agreement is set to take effect July 1995. 
  "This dumping would greatly prejudice local manufacturers or 
similar goods because they would find it difficult to 
restructure their capital requirements and update their 
factories, plant facilities, and their inventories," Shahani 
warned. Shahani said that uncontrolled dumping of goods from 
abroad would impair the ability of Philippine industries to 
compete in the world market. 
  President Ramos and the senators led by Senate President 
Edgardo J. Angara, in their third regular Tuesday breakfast 
meeting this week agreed to ask Trade Secretary Rizalino Navarro 
to create a panel of Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) 
experts to provide accurate data on the GATT which would help 
senators understand the complexities of the international 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5588 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas046_l_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-046 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

