<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Over $1.4 Billion in Foreign Funds Invested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0903072494 Manila MANILA BULLETIN in English 6 Mar 94 p b-1 </F>
<F P=103> BK0903072494 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] More than $1.4 billion in foreign funds came into 
the country as portfolio investments in 1993. Bangko Sentral ng 
Pilipinas [Central Bank of the Philippines] (BSP) statistics 
showed that bulk of the foreign capital was lodged in the 
equities markets. This capital placements fuelled the bull run 
in the domestic stock market in 1993, particularly during the 
later months. 
  Out of the $1 429 billion, about $808.632 million or 56.59 
percent, was invested in stocks, mostly of commercial and 
industrial listed companies. The balance was invested in banks, 
which included registered bank deposits of non-residents, 
government securities paper, utility and investment and finance 
firms. 
  Of the commercial and industrial classifications, a sizable 
amount, around $468.795 million, went to buy shares of listed 
telecommunications companies. This amount push the shares of 
Philippines Long Distance Co. last year as the highest gainer in 
the stock market. [passage omitted] 
  BSP said that these foreign funds lodged in the local 
bourses 
put the country in the international map as among the emerging 
stock markets in the region. As has been reported, the country's 
stock market registered the best ever performance in the recent 
years with a record high of 150 percent growth in 1993. Trading 
in both bourses were heavy particularly during the last days of 
December, posting at one time the highest turnover of P4.26 
billion [Philippine pesos]. 

</TEXT>

