<F P=102>  BK0903100994 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 9 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0903100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] Australia has called on the 
United States to maintain China's most favored nation trade 
privileges. Speaking after talks with Mr. Christopher, 
Australia's foreign minister, Gareth Evans, said he shared 
Washington's concern at the detention and harassment of Chinese 
dissidents. Senator Evans said protesting at this was not a 
matter of interfering in China's internal affairs or applying 
Western standards. But Senator Evans said Australia was against 
trade sanctions, except in extreme circumstances and supported 
continued privileges for China under the MFN scheme. 
  Meanwhile, Mr. Christopher has repeated an assurance that 
Washington does not intend its trade dispute with Japan to do 
harm to Australia. He gave the reassurance after talks in 
Canberra with Senator Evans and the trade minister, Senator Bob 
McMullan. Camille Funnell reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Funnell] The U.S. secretary of state told 
the Australians it was not the intention of the U.S. to start a 
trade war with Japan, but he repeated that America wanted 
greater access to the Japanese market. He says Australia should 
take heart about American assurances from the track record of 
U.S. President Bill Clinton. [passage omitted] Senator Evans 
says Australia still has legitimate concerns about the approach 
taken by the U.S. toward Japan and will continue to express its 
concern. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

