<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kantor: U.S. Not After `Trend Line' Targets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803234894 Tokyo KYODO in English 2303 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803234894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 8 KYODO -- U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor denied Tuesday [8 March] that the 
United States has sought Japanese assurances to increase the 
market share of a U.S.-developed cellular phone system in Japan 
according to prearranged growth projections. 
  KYODO NEWS SERVICE reported Monday that the U.S. has 
proposed 
using "numerical indicators" that would give the cellular system 
developed and built by Motorola Inc. an additional 240,000 
subscribers after one year in the Tokyo and Nagoya areas. 
  "That report is erroneous," Kantor said. 
  Kantor, responding to a reporter's question, said the U.S. 
has not sought more Motorola cellular subscribers by the 
business trend line the U.S. firm has established elsewhere in 
Japan. 
  The Motorola system, which signed up 12,900 cellular 
subscribers in the Tokyo and Nagoya areas after two years in 
service, has 438,000 subscribers elsewhere in the country, 
mostly in the Kansai area, after four years in operation. 
  Kantor has accused Tokyo of violating a 1989 trade accord 
that promises "comparable access" to Motorola in the Japanese 
market and has vowed to impose sanctions against Japan if no 
settlement is reached through negotiations. 
  While denying the U.S. has sought trend line sales targets, 
Kantor declined to discuss whether other types of numerical 
targets are in the U.S. proposal on grounds that negotiations 
are currently continuing between Motorola and its Japanese 
business partner Nippon Idou Tsushin Corp. 
  Nippon Idou offers both Motorola and a rival Japanese 
cellular phone system for its cellular service in the lucrative 
Tokyo and Nagoya areas, home to 60 million Japanese consumers. 
  The U.S. Government is set to announce by Thursday next week 
a target list of Japanese products that will be subject to U.S. 
sanctions if no settlement is reached over the cellular 
telephone dispute. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

