<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on U.S. Secretary of State's Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903100994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0938 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher flies to Tokyo Wednesday [9 March] night for 
the first direct top-level contact between Japan and the U.S. 
since President Bill Clinton and Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa met in Washington last month. 
  During his three-day visit, Christopher will meet Hosokawa 
and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata on Thursday for talks on 
bilateral economic problems. 
  Hata and Christopher will also hold "two-plus-two" 
ministerial security talks with Defense Agency chief Kazuo Aichi 
and U.S. Undersecretary of Defense Frank Wisner on Friday 
morning. 
  Bilateral relations took a turn for the worse last month 
when 
Clinton and Hosokawa announced the collapse of bilateral trade 
"framework" negotiations aimed at redressing Japan's more than 
60 billion dollar trade surplus with the United States. 
  That prompted the U.S. Government to reinstate a trade law 
known as "Super 301" which gives it powers to impose sanctions 
against countries it holds guilty of unfair trade practices. 
The action is widely understood to be aimed at pressuring Japan 
into opening its market and reducing its trade surplus. 
  Foreign ministry sources said the failed talks are likely to 
be high on the agenda. 
  The Japanese are expected to explain their market-opening 
package and seek U.S. understanding, while expressing concern 
over the reinstatement of Super 301, according to the sources. 
  Hosokawa and Christopher are also likely to discuss China, 
since Christopher will fly to Beijing after leaving Tokyo on 
Friday and Hosokawa is scheduled to visit China from March 19 to 
21. 
  Christopher will also attend an international conference on 
aid to Cambodia in Tokyo on Thursday and deliver a speech to 
business leaders on Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5610 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas046_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-046 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Focus' of Meetings Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903092394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0902 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- The first Japan-U.S. 
foreign affairs and defense "two-plus-two" talks will be held 
Friday morning at the prime minister's official residence, 
government sources said Wednesday [9 March]. 
  Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and Defense Agency Chief Kazuo 
Aichi will meet U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and 
Undersecretary of Defense Frank Wisner for a discussion of 
bilateral and regional security issues. 
  Coming as concerns grow over Japan-U.S. trade relations, the 
talks are intended to promote understanding between Tokyo and 
Washington in order to prevent trade frictions from affecting 
political and security affairs, the sources said. 
  The talks are expected to focus on North Korea's suspected 
nuclear weapons development program and the strengthening of the 
military in China as well as touching upon the issue of U.S. 
military bases in Okinawa. 
  The meeting is also likely to consider revisions to Japanese 
defense plans in the post-Cold War world and military reductions 
by the United States, the sources suggested. 
  Until December 1990, the security talks had been attended by 
the U.S. Ambassador to Japan and the commander of the U.S. 
forces in the Pacific with the foreign minister and the Defense 
Agency director general. 
  It was agreed to upgrade the talks, but the higher level 
talks have yet to be held because of the changes in the 
international situation. 
  Wisner is accompanying Christopher on his three-nation tour 
of the Asia-Pacific region and will attend the talks for 
Secretary of Defense William Perry who did not make the trip. 

</TEXT>

