<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ozawa Plans To Visit U.S. on Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903052294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0441 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903052294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- An influential politician in 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's coalition government Ichiro 
Ozawa plans to visit Washington by the end of March in an effort 
to break the deadlock in stalled bilateral economic framework 
talks, government sources said Wednesday [9 March]. 
  Ozawa, co-leader of Shinseito, one of the ruling seven 
parties, wants to visit the United States for talks with top 
U.S. lawmakers on Capitol Hill, the sources said. 
  According to Shinseito leaders, the government has yet to 
decide on sending Ozawa as special envoy, but Prime Minister 
Hosokawa may have unofficially asked Ozawa to go, they said. 
  Following the collapse of the framework trade talks between 
Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill Clinton in February, the 
Japanese Government will announce by the end of March a plan to 
reduce Japan's huge trade surplus and to open up various 
markets, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

