<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDO, Motorola Reach `Broad' Phone Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903121094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1145 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Nippon Idou Tsushin Corp. 
(IDO) has reached a broad agreement with Motorola Inc. of the 
United States over Motorola's demand for more access to the 
Japanese mobile telephone market, industrial sources said 
Wednesday. 
  Motorola Vice President Arnold Brenner arrived in Tokyo on 
Wednesday to finalize negotiations. 
  IDO said it hopes to straighten out differences over the 
issue by the end of this week. 
  The accord would help avoid U.S. trade retaliation against 
Japan. The U.S. Trade Representative Office has set March 17 as 
the deadline for an announcement on sanctions over trade issues. 
  IDO and Motorola were near agreement over the timing of an 
expansion of a network of Motorola-formula car phone relay 
stations and an allocation of radio frequencies, IDO officials 
said. 
  They said Motorola has agreed to IDO's offer to increase the 
number of relay stations, which will total 190 at the end of 
June, by an additional 159 stations. 
  But the officials said Motorola demanded that the network 
expansion be completed within the next one and a half years, 
while IDO contends that the project will take more than two 
years. 
  IDO was also resisting Motorola's demand that part of the 
frequencies allotted for Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) 
formula transmission be transferred to its service in Japan on 
the ground of high costs, the officials said. 
  They said the frequency switch to the Motorola formula is 
almost impossible because it requires remodeling all NTT-formula 
relay stations, which would require an investment of tens of 
billions of yen. 
  Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's top automaker and a major 
investor in IDO, is set to help finance the project by 
increasing IDO's capital through a new share issue, they said. 

</TEXT>

