<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chrysler `Cherokee' Models Sales Limit Raised </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903124794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1227 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- The Transport Ministry said 
Wednesday it has granted Chrysler Corp.'s four-wheel drive 
"Cherokee" model a type certificate that allows the U.S. car 
maker to sell more than 2,000 cars of the model a year in Japan. 
  Ministry officials said there have been three models of 
American cars granted the certificate, with a condition that 
sales agents remodel the cars after importing to ensure they 
meet Japan's industrial standards. 
  This time, however, no such condition was given on the 
Cherokees, they said. 
  Currently, Chrysler plans to sell some 7,000 Cherokee model 
cars on the Japanese market at about 3 million to 3.73 million 
yen per unit. 
  In line with its domestic industrial and safety standards, 
Japan sets standards for goods to be imported to Japan. 
  It has been charged by other countries, including the United 
States, that the system is a nontariff trade barrier. 
  The ministry sent officials to the U.S. to deliver the 
certificate to Chrysler and to visit other manufacturers such as 
General Motors Corp. to explain the nature of the system and 
requirements for obtaining the certificate, officials said. 

</TEXT>

