<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cambodian Officials Begin Four-Day Visit 9 Mar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Door Reportedly Still Open to KR </H4>
<F P=102> OW0903150294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1452 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903150294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Cambodian First Prime 
Minister Norodom Ranariddh said Wednesday the royal government 
is "keeping the door open to the Khmer Rouge [KR]," Foreign 
Ministry officials said. 
  But Ranariddh, making the remarks in a dinner meeting with 
Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, said it will not do for 
the Khmer Rouge to try to "bargain" its way through the door. 
  Rather, the guerrilla group must enter through dialogue with 
the government on national reconciliation in a sincere manner, 
he was quoted as saying. 
  Ranariddh, who arrived in Tokyo earlier in the day to attend 
a two-day international aid conference beginning Thursday, did 
not clarify what role the Khmer Rouge could be given in the 
future political makeup of the country. 
  He previously rejected proposals to give the Khmer Rouge 
posts in the cabinet in exchange for a return of territories 
under its control and integration of its guerrilla army into the 
nation's unified armed forces. 
  The officials said Ranariddh said it is not permissible that 
the Khmer Rouge continues to control large tracts of territory. 
The guerrilla group, which held the nation under a rule of 
terror from 1975 to 1978, still controls an estimated 15 to 20 
percent of the country's territory. 
  Ranariddh said the Khmer Rouge has not responded to the 
governments repeated calls for a ceasefire despite the fact that 
repeated concessions have been made to them. He suggested the 
ball is now in the court of the guerrilla group. 
  Ranariddh made the remarks in the wake of message issued by 
ailing Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk in Beijing calling for a 
ceasefire. 
  "The war between the Royal Cambodian Armed Forces and the 
Democratic Kampuchea (Khmer Rouge) forces has so far brought 
nothing but destruction, separation, suffering, pain, shame and 
despair for Cambodia, for our nation and especially our poor 
people," the king said in a statement dated March 7. 
  Khmer Rouge nominal leader Khieu Samphan has reportedly 
responded by expressing support for Sihanouk. 
  Government forces are reportedly preparing an attack on the 
Khmer Rouge's headquarters in Pailin, some 300 kilometers 
northwest of Phnom Penh near the Thai border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

