<H3> <TI>   Cambodian Officials Begin Four-Day Visit 9 Mar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sirivut Proposes `Partnership' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0903122694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1149 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Cambodian Foreign Minister 
Norodom Sirivut called Wednesday [9 March] for the forging of a 
"dependable partnership" between Cambodia and Japan in the 
political and economic realms, Japanese Foreign Ministry 
officials said. 
  The officials said Sirivut made the call in a half-hour 
meeting with Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata. Both 
Sirivut and Hata serve concurrently as foreign ministers and 
deputy prime ministers. 
  Sirivut arrived in Tokyo earlier in the day accompanying 
Co-Premiers Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Hun Sen to a two-day 
meeting of the International Committee on the Reconstruction of 
Cambodia (ICORC), which starts Thursday. 
  He was quoted as saying that in order to further consolidate 
ties between Cambodia and Japan his government is considering an 
early reopening of its embassy in Tokyo. 
  Since the fall of the Lon Nol government to the Khmer Rouge 
in 1975, the embassy in Tokyo's Akasaka District has been 
occupied by Cambodians of various political persuasions but it 
has not been functioning in an official capacity. 
  Officials said Sirivut told Hata Cambodia is requesting 
assistance from the international community from the perspective 
that its own self-help efforts are most important. 
  They said Hata called such an approach laudable and 
expressed 
hope that the ICORC meeting will prove successful in 
facilitating Cambodia's development. 
  Hata said that if Cambodia's reconstruction from years of 
civil strife goes smoothly it could serve as a model for similar 
efforts in other parts of the world. 

</TEXT>

