<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa To Offer Support for PRC Reforms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903120194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1142 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa will express Japan's support for China's open reform 
policies when he visits China from March 19 to 21, Foreign 
Ministry officials said Wednesday [9 March]. 
  He will also support China's bid to become a member of the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), the officials 
said. 
  Hosokawa will voice the support in a series of talks with 
Chinese leaders, including Chinese President Jiang Zemin, 
Premier Li Peng and Qiao Shi, chairman of the National People's 
Congress Standing Committee, they said. 
  He will also talk about Japan's yen loans to China, they 
said. 
  When Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata visited China in January, 
Japan and China agreed to divide Japan's loan periods from five 
years to three-year and two-year periods beginning with the 1996 
fiscal year. 
  Hosokawa and Chinese leaders will also discuss boosting 
Japanese investment and cooperation between the two nations on 
environmental preservation, they said. 
  They will also exchange views on international affairs such 
as cooperation in the Asia-Pacific region and North Korea's 
alleged nuclear weapons development program, they said. 
  Hosokawa is scheduled to arrive in Beijing on March 19 and 
visit Shanghai on March 21 before returning to Tokyo. 
  The last visit to China by a Japanese prime minister was in 
1991 when then Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu visited China and 
Mongolia. 

</TEXT>

