<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Defense Panel on International Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903032294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0301 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903032294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- A private defense panel to 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Wednesday [9 March] 
discussed post-Cold War developments around the world and the 
military situation surrounding Japan. 
  The nine-member group, asked to review Japan's 
two-decade-old 
defense policies, exchanged views after listening to briefings 
from officials of the Foreign Ministry and the Defense Agency, 
the panel chairman told a news conference. 
  The group spent considerable time discussing the Foreign 
Ministry's explanation that the world is in a transition period 
after the end of the Cold War, said Hirotaro Higuchi, also 
chairman of Asahi Breweries Ltd. 
  Many group members raised doubts about the notion, arguing 
that frameworks already exist to maintain a new world order such 
as the Group of Seven (G-7) industrial nations and the United 
Nations Security Council, Higuchi said. 
  The next meeting of the panel is scheduled for March 16. 
  The panel, after debating overall defense matters once a 
week, will offer recommendations to Hosokawa by around summer 
for a revision of the National Defense Program Outline, which 
has served as Japan's basic defense policy since 1976, 
  Based on the panel's recommendations, defense policies, 
including Japan's future role in U.N.-led peacekeeping 
operations, will likely be revised in time for inclusion in the 
Defense Agency's budget requests for fiscal 1995. 
  Higuchi denied the possibility of the panel discussing the 
interpretation of the current war-renouncing constitution, 
saying the group will talk about defense matters within the 
scope of the current constitution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

