<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Kajima-Nakamura Scandal Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kajima Firm, Nakamura Home Raided </H4>
<F P=102> OW0903053894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0511 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903053894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Prosecutors raided the head 
office of Kajima Corp. and the homes of its top executives and 
former Construction Minister Kishiro Nakamura on Wednesday [8 
March] in connection with Nakamura's alleged acceptance of a 10 
million yen bribe from the construction giant. 
  The raids covered more than 30 locations which included the 
homes of Rokuro Ishikawa, chairman of Kajima, and Akira 
Miyazaki, president. 
  Meanwhile, the House of Representatives Steering Committee 
convened Wednesday to listen to Justice Ministry officials to 
discuss a request by prosecutors to arrest Nakamura, a member of 
the house, who quit the main opposition Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) earlier in the day. 
  Committee Chairman Keiwa Okuda told reporters later that the 
lower house needs to decide on the request as early as possible. 
  Diet permission is required for the arrest of 
parliamentarians while the legislature is in session. The Diet 
is currently in a 150-day ordinary session that started in late 
January. 
  Investigators from the Tokyo District Public Prosecutors 
Office will soon ask Ishikawa, 68, to voluntarily submit to 
questions pertaining to the money allegedly paid in January 1992 
to Nakamura, investigative sources said. 
  Ishikawa formerly served as head of the Japan Chamber of 
Commerce and Industry, one of Japan's four top business 
organizations, and also of the Japan Federation of Construction 
Contractors Inc., an industry association of general contractors. 
  He resigned as president of the chamber last year as 
prosecutors promoted probes into the widening scandal involving 
politicians and contractors. 
  Investigators have already quizzed Miyazaki, 70, the 
president of Kajima, one of Japan's top contractors. 
  On Tuesday, prosecutors again arrested a former vice 
president of Kajima, Shinji Kiyoyama, 67, on suspicion of giving 
the 10 million yen bribe to Nakamura. 
  Nakamura allegedly received the money as a reward for using 
his influence to help prevent the Fair Trade Commission (FTC) 
from lodging a criminal complaint against contractors including 
Kajima, for bid-rigging in Saitama Prefecture. 
  Kiyoyama allegedly asked Nakamura, a senior member of the 
LDP's construction lobby, to put pressure on the FTC not to file 
an accusation with prosecutors against a bid-rigging cartel 
involving Kajima and 65 other construction firms. 
  At the time, Nakamura was the deputy chairman of the LDP's 
panel on the Antimonopoly Law. The LDP was in power for 38 
years until the inauguration of the coalition government of 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa last August. 
  Nakamura later served as construction minister from December 
1992 to August 1993 under then Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa. 
  Investigators intend to question fallen LDP kingpin Shin 
Kanemaru, 79, who is being tried in a separate income tax 
evasion case, the investigative sources said. 
  Prosecutors suspect Kiyoyama first asked Kanemaru to put 
pressure on the FTC, an antitrust watchdog body. Kanemaru 
allegedly replied that Nakamura was handling the matter, the 
sources said. 
  Kiyoyama and three other former Kajima officials were 
indicted last year in two bribery cases. Prosecutors said the 
Kajima officials gave 20 million yen to former Ibaraki Gov. 
Fujio Takeuchi and 10 million yen to former Sendai Mayor Toru 
Ishii. 

</TEXT>

