<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Kajima-Nakamura Scandal Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa: Prosecutors To Do Duty </H4>
<F P=102> OW0903053994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0515 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903053994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Wednesday [9 March] the government is convinced 
prosecutors will carry out their duty with law and justice in a 
case involving former Construction Minister Kishiro Nakamura 
suspected of taking a bribe from major general contractor Kajima 
Corp. 
  Hosokawa, replying to questions from Hiroshi Tachiki of the 
Japanese Communist Party (JCP) in the House of Councillors 
plenary session, said the government "will wait and see how the 
investigation develops." 
  Nakamura, 44, who bolted from the main opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) on Wednesday, is suspected of taking a 10 
million yen bribe from Kajima in January 1992, investigative 
sources said. 
  On Tuesday, prosecutors asked Tokyo district court to issue 
an arrest warrant for him. The court submitted a document to 
the cabinet asking for Diet permission to lift parliamentary 
immunity on Nakamura from arrest. The cabinet in turn passed it 
to the House of Representatives, to which Nakamura belongs. 
  The Diet is currently in the middle of a 150-day regular 
session due to end in June. 

</TEXT>

