<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii: Economy Still Mixed, in `Delicate' Stage </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903102294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0958 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- The economy remains "mixed" 
and in a "delicate stage" with some improvements seen in recent 
indicators such as consumption and production, Finance Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii said Wednesday [9 March]. 
  Speaking at a regular press meeting, Fujii backed off from 
comments he made Sunday in an informal speech made in Tochigi 
Prefecture, in which he indicated "as his personal view" that 
the economy had hit bottom. 
  "This is an official press meeting," he said, brushing aside 
further questions on his earlier remarks. 
  Fujii also repeated that he is "confident that steady 
implementation of the latest 15.25 trillion stimulus package 
will put the economy on a recovery track in fiscal 1994." 
  The finance minister declined to comment on a meeting of 
cabinet ministers earlier on Wednesday to discuss Japan's 
"voluntary" market-opening package to address the ongoing trade 
dispute with the United States. 
  He described the meeting as "free talking," but declined to 
comment further. 
  The reason for the hastily-arranged meeting was seen to 
allow 
discussion over Japan's stance before Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata meet U.S. Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher, who is scheduled to arrive in Tokyo 
for an official visit Wednesday night. 
  Asked about the latest U.S. stance of not reopening trade 
talks, Fujii said that Japan would "positively" take its 
"voluntary measures" aside from negotiations. 
  Meanwhile, Fujii reiterated that the government is not 
considering a plan to boost the 10-year public works program of 
430 billion yen as part of the package. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

