<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Committee To Monitor Deregulation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903083594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0816 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- The government on Wednesday 
[9 March] came up with the outline of a bill to establish an 
administrative reform committee in order to monitor the progress 
of Japan's economic deregulation, officials said. 
  They said the proposed legislation is expected to be 
presented to a meeting of the ruling coalition's policy-making 
officials Thursday and is likely to be approved by the cabinet 
on March 18 for presentation to the current Diet. 
  The committee is expected to promote the easing of existing 
economic restrictions, discuss the opening of government-held 
information to the public and make recommendations to the prime 
minister on the basis of its surveys and discussions. 
  Under the proposed bill, the five-member committee with a 
three-year tenure will be created in the prime minister's office 
and will function like other advisory councils appointed by the 
prime minister, the officials said. 
  One or two of the members will serve full-time on the 
committee. 
  Some lawmakers have expressed doubts about the proposal to 
establish a committee in the government to monitor the 
government's economic deregulation. 

</TEXT>

