<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mining Industry Leaders Ask for Government Help </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903032094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0247 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903032094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Mining industry leaders 
Wednesday [9 March] asked the Trade Ministry to take steps to 
spur demand for mineral products. 
  Presidents of major mining companies belonging to the Japan 
Mining Industry Association made the request in a breakfast 
meeting with Hiroshi Kumagai, international trade and industry 
minister. 
  Mining companies are struggling due to slack demand from the 
auto and precious metals industries, the presidents of Sumitomo 
Metal Mining Co., Mitsubishi Materials Corp., Dowa Mining Co. 
and other companies told Kumagai. 
  They also requested the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry (MITI) to promote a policy to ensure "smooth purchases" 
abroad of mineral ores. 
  Kumagai told the executives the ministry will work hard to 
help the mining industry by improving fiscal and tax systems, 
MITI officials said. 

</TEXT>

