<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industries Cited for Possible Super 301 Action </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803234994 Tokyo KYODO in English 2308 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803234994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 8 KYODO -- U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor Tuesday [8 March] raised the 
possibility that up to eight Japanese industries would be 
subject to retaliatory action under the so-called "Super 301" 
trade law. 
  Kantor identified wood, paper, flat glass, computers, 
supercomputers, telecommunications, medical equipment, and 
insurance as business areas where he said U.S. firms face 
barriers in penetrating the Japanese market. 
  President Bill Clinton reinstated the Super 301 trade 
provision by executive order last week, setting in motion a U.S. 
policy of removing foreign trade barriers by targeting offending 
trading partners for retaliation. 
  Under Clinton's executive order, U.S. trading partners 
accused of maintaining trade barriers against U.S. goods have 
until September 30 to avoid being singled out for possible Super 
301 action. 
  Testifying before a House Appropriations Subcommittee that 
handles trade matters Tuesday, Kantor named the eight Japanese 
industry sectors as areas which he said do not meet U.S. 
market-opening criteria. 
  Kantor in particular cited wood, paper and flat glass as 
three Japanese market sectors where he said U.S. firms have seen 
a decline in their market share. 
  The U.S. Government is scheduled to issue an annual review 
on 
foreign trade barriers by the end of March, setting off a 
six-month process of preliminary negotiations to remove what 
Washington views as the "most egregious" practices. 
  Kantor indicated that U.S. jaw-boning is unlikely to resolve 
all trade disputes, telling the U.S. legislators that it would 
be "quite unusual" if the Super 301 priority list turns up empty 
on September 30. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

