<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kubota Opposes Targets To Cut Trade Surplus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2602224794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Feb 
94 Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2602224794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a news conference following a meeting of the 
cabinet on 25 February, Manae Kubato, director general of the 
Economic Planning Agency [EPA], opposed the idea of setting 
targets for reducing Japan's current-accounts surplus. She 
said, "The current-accounts surplus is the most difficult 
economic factor for the government to control." She also said, 
"I understand that Japan has maintained the principles of free 
trade in the Japanese-U.S. economic framework talks." In this 
way, Kubota indicated that setting any kind of numerical target 
could lead to managed trade. 

</TEXT>

