<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Businessman: Cellular Phone Market Open </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303061094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Feb 
94 Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0303061094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] With regard to the Japan-U.S. friction over 
cellular phones, the United States pronounced Japan "guilty" of 
closing its market. However, Morgan Bengtson [name as 
published], president of Ericsson Japan (located in Xinato Ward, 
Tokyo) said: "With regard to cellular phones, the Japanese 
market is open. The highest priorities should be given to 
technological capabilities and prices in an open, competitive 
system. It is not good that (the market principle) is twisted 
by political pressures." His remarks can be seen as "coming to 
Japan's rescue." 
  Bengtson also said: "A trade imbalance surely exists between 
Japan and the United States. However, there is a possibility 
that U.S. policies (on the cellular phone issue) will work 
against the free trade system. It is not desirable for American 
companies to have an advantage in the Japanese market because of 
such policies." He questioned the U.S. strategy of demanding 
numerical targets by threatening the possibility of sanctions 
against Japan. 
  Ericsson Japan is a subsidiary of the major Swedish 
electrical manufacturer Ericsson Company. Ericsson Japan has 
succeeded in receiving orders for radio base stations for 
cellular phones worth about 40 billion yen from NTT Mobile 
Communications Network Company and Tokyo Digital Phone Company 
(located in Chiyoda Ward, Tokyo; president, Susumu Ochiai). 
Thus, it is believed that Ericsson cannot remain indifferent to 
this Japan-U.S. friction. 

</TEXT>

