<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Media Understanding Sought on Phone Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303200794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0303200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Shigeru Komago in Washington] </F>
  [Text] On 28 February, the Japanese Embassy in the United 
States began to send officials to visit major U.S. newspapers to 
explain its view on the U.S. Trade Representative's (USTR) 
charge that Japan has violated an agreement in the portable and 
car phone sector. The embassy seeks to gain the U.S. news 
media's understanding by explaining that "the USTR's charge is 
full of errors." But some people are cool toward this, saying: 
"What Japan should do promptly is to talk with the U.S. 
Government rather than do public relations work with the news 
media." 
  The embassy, after consulting with the Ministry of Posts and 
Telecommunications, prepared a paper entitled "Refutation of the 
USTR's Claim" in English, and explained it to newspapers like 
THE WASHINGTON POST and THE WALL STREET JOURNAL individually. 
In the paper, the embassy rebuts almost all points raised by 
USTR Mickey Kantor on 15 February as violations of an agreement 
by Japan. The paper cites specific reasons in refuting the U.S. 
charge as a "misunderstanding of facts" or an "incomprehensible 
assertion." 
  The U.S. news media, in reporting on the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks, took the position of criticizing the Clinton 
administration with respect to its demands for objective 
criteria, thus making favorable reports on Japan. But as far as 
the portable and car phone issue was concerned, the news media 
supported the USTR's assertion, and most major newspapers 
criticized Japan in their editorials. Given this situation, 
Japan appears to have decided that it should do public relations 
work with the U.S. news media in this regard. 
  After listening to Japan's explanation, a major newspaper's 
reporter gave a wry smile and said: "I see that the U.S demands 
are rather unreasonable. But what surprises me most is that the 
Japanese and the U.S. Governments are too different in their 
perceptions and stands." Another said: "The gaps between the 
two governments should be filled by the governments themselves. 
The news media cannot do that for them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

