<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Opposed to Motorola Phone Market Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803143594 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0803143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Shigeru Komago] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 7 Mar -- It was learned on the morning 
of 7 March that Motorola Inc. of the United States made a new 
proposal on the opening of the Japanese mobile and car phone 
market. The new proposal demands that Japan increase 
Motorola-formula mobile and car phones by about 240,000 in a 
year in service areas between Tokyo and Nagoya. Japan considers 
the proposal a demand for setting a numerical target, thus it 
is opposed to it. Because of this, negotiations between Japan 
and the United States over opening Japan's cellular phone market 
may become rough at the final stage. Nevertheless, because the 
proposal is not an official one put forward by the U.S. Trade 
Representative Office, Tokyo thinks that "we will eventually be 
able to persuade the United States to withdraw the proposal." 

</TEXT>

