<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura on Possibility of Voluntary Targets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903134994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0903134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the plenary sessions of both the House of 
Representatives and the House of Councillors on 7 and 8 March, 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa was asked about the issue of 
setting numerical targets to reduce Japan's current account 
surplus, which is a focal issue in trade friction between Japan 
and the United States. He answered: "It is inappropriate to 
set specific numerical targets." 
  Commenting on this at a news conference on the evening of 8 
March, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura said: "The 
prime minister and I share the same view that setting numerical 
targets is very difficult. However, it is unnecessary to assert 
that it will never happen (for Japan to set numerical targets). 
Mr. Hosokawa has not yet made a final decision." Takemura then 
added: "Current account surplus bears more uncertain factors 
than any other economic indexes. At least, Japan should not set 
numerical targets as a pledge to the international community and 
make a commitment to the United States." 
  Takemura's remark indicates that although Japan should never 
commit to Washington about setting numerical targets to reduce 
its current account surplus, it is possible that it will 
voluntarily set targets for reducing the surplus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

