<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Rejects U.S. Plea on Caning Verdict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0803150794 Singapore Singapore Broadcasting Corporation in 
English 1400 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0803150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore Singapore Broadcasting Corporation </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Foreign Ministry says the law in Singapore must 
take its course and the ministry cannot be expected to intervene 
in the due process of the law. This is the ministry's response 
to the U.S. Embassy here over its concern on the caning sentence 
passed by the court on an American teenager, Michael Fay. The 
ministry noted that Fay's sentencing was the outcome of a fair 
and transparent legal process. Fay was given every opportunity 
to defend himself with representation and counsel of his choice. 
It stressed that the Singapore judicial process cannot apply 
different standards to persons subjected to the same law. 
Therefore, it is not correct for the U.S. to say based on the 
facts on the treatment of other similar cases, this punishment 
is extreme. 
  The ministry pointed out that Fay is not the first teenaged 
person nor foreigner to have received the sentence of caning 
under the Vandalism Act. Twelve Singaporeans and two 
foreigners, aged 18 to 21, have received caning sentences for 
vandalism since 1989. The ministry cited some previous 
vandalism cases. In 1990, a 20-year-old Singaporean was 
sentenced to a month jail and three strokes for damaging public 
property. Last year, there was a similar case where a 
19-year-old Singaporean was sentenced to three months jail and 
three strokes of a cane. The ministry said in contrast to these 
cases, Fay admitted in all to 18 counts of vandalism and six 
counts of misdeeds. These facts, among others, show that the 
court sentence meted out to Fay is neither extreme nor 
unprecedented. Fay, who is 18, was sentenced last Thursday to 
four months in prison and six strokes of a cane for vandalism. 
Fay is appealing against the sentence and he is currently on a 
[Singapore] $75,000 bail. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

