<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Structural Reform `Priority' of G-7 Job Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803091394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0737 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803091394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 8 KYODO -- The seven leading 
industrialized countries will place top priority on structural 
reforms to promote employment during the jobs summit in Detroit 
next week, government sources said Tuesday [8 March]. 
  The Group of Seven (G-7) nations apparently will adopt the 
chairman's draft statement noting that international trade will 
help boost employment, baring in mind the relation between trade 
surpluses and unemployment. 
  The statement, to be released after the two-day summit, will 
avoid singling out individual nations for criticism. But Japan 
may be the exception if the nation leaves its huge trade surplus 
untouched, the sources said. 
  The economic ministers of the G-7 countries will participate 
in the jobs summit, to be held March 14 and 15. Labor Minister 
Chikara Sakaguchi will represent Japan. 
  According to the sources, these are the main points of the 
chairman's statement: 
  -- Major industrial nations have been battling against 
unemployment. 
  -- The unemployment rate has been rising in Europe and 
Japan, whose rate is the smallest among the G-7 nations. 
  -- Each nation needs to provide equal opportunities to all 
workers, particularly those in the low-skill sector. 
  -- Structural reforms will only be effective when they are 
supplemented and supported by appropriate macroeconomic policies. 
  -- International trade is essential to boost wealth, 
employment and wages. 
  -- The development of new technology regarding data 
processing, has the potential to increase the wealth of 
participating nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

