<H3> <TI>   Editor Urged To Quit for `Straining' UK Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0803150294 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in Malay 
1300 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0803150294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Malay </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The UMNO [United Nalays National Organization] 
Youth Movement has urged Andrew Neil, chief editor of the SUNDAY 
TIMES, to resign for straining relations between Malaysia and 
Britain and causing British companies to incur huge losses as 
they are no longer allowed to bid for Malaysian Government 
contracts. Tan Sri Haji Abdul Rahim Tamby Chik, chairman of the 
UMNO Youth Movement, said it would be good for the SUNDAY TIMES 
to promise not to publish baseless and untrue reports about 
Malaysia to ensure that the economic interests of the two 
nations are maintained. In a statement issued in Melaka, the 
movement also severely criticized the provocative attitude of 
the SUNDAY TIMES, which urged the British Government to 
retaliate against Malaysia by freezing payments to the Pergau 
hydroelectric plant project. Malaysia should be prepared for 
any eventuality, in case the British Government is really forced 
to bow to the wishes and pressure of the SUNDAY TIMES which led 
to the Malaysian Government's decision not to award government 
contracts to British companies. 

</TEXT>

