<H3> <TI>   Hiraiwa Backs Private-Sector Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503014494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0503014494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of Keidanren [Japan 
Federation of Economic Organizations], at a news conference in 
Nagoya city on 3 March, commented on the issue of setting 
sector-by-sector numerical targets over which Japan and the 
United States failed to reach agreement at the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks. 
  Hiraiwa said this issue should be settled by the industries 
of the two nations, insisting: "The problem should be resolved 
not by governments setting numbers, but by the private sectors 
talking to each other." He added: "Negotiations are continuing 
and we will try to find a compromise through these negotiations." 

