<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Groups Offer Plans on Trade Friction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003000194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1003000194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Keidanren [Japan Federation of Economic 
Organizations] and the Keizai Doyukai [Japan Association of 
Corporate Executives] compiled on 7 March the agenda of their 
respective emergency proposals concerning Japan-U.S. relations, 
in which a crack is developing in the wake of the recent 
Japan-U.S. summit talks. The Keidanren, in its agenda of 
proposals, asks the government to revise the basic plan for 
public investment totaling 430 trillion yen on which Japan and 
the United States agreed three years ago and to add more than 
100 trillion yen. The Keizai Doyukai, in its agenda of 
proposals, calls on the government to 1) add 100 trillion yen 
for public investment, 2) reduce Japan's current account surplus 
to about 2 percent of its GDP (gross national product) three 
years later, 3) cut the income tax, not for one year, but for at 
least three years prior to raising the consumption tax, and 4) 
work out an action program to narrow price differentials between 
Japan and other nations. The two economic organizations have 
submitted their proposals to the prime minister. 
  On 7 March, the president and vice presidents of Keidanren 
met to compile the agenda of emergency proposals entitled "View 
on Aggressive Solution of Japan-U.S. Issues." The Keizai 
Doyukai inaugurated an ad hoc committee shortly after the recent 
Japan-U.S. summit talks broke off to study ways to compile the 
agenda of the emergency proposal. As reasons for making the 
emergency proposal, the Keidanren says, "the United States is 
moving to slap sanctions on Japan over the mobile phone issue 
after the Super 301 provision was revived, and a sense of crisis 
is growing at home." Keizai Doyukai President Masaru Hayami 
says, "Both Japan and the United States should restore mutual 
trust at the earliest date." A growing sense of crisis among 
business leaders has prompted the two economic organizations to 
compile the agenda of their emergency proposals. 
  The Keidanren, in its agenda of proposals, calls for 
increasing the amount of public investment, thoroughly relaxing 
bureaucratic regulations, taking measures to help foreign firms 
gain access to the Japanese market through the removal of import 
and investment barriers, implementing properly a competitive 
policy, and reducing areas subject to exclusion from the 
competitive policy. As for the revival of the Super 301 
provision, the Keidanren makes clear its view that Japan should 
take its case to GATT if necessary, saying, "Japan should handle 
a bilateral trade dispute with the United States in GATT, and a 
hollowing out of international organizations and systems should 
be prevented." 
  The Keizai Doyukai makes concrete proposals to Japanese 
enterprises, U.S. corporations, the Japanese Government, and the 
U.S. Government. In its concrete proposals, the Keizai Doyukai 
asks Japanese enterprises to stop exporting goods at below 
production costs, aggressively purchase equipment and raw 
materials from abroad, address Japan's traditional trade 
practices, and rebuild their structure of business and 
production, and asks U.S. corporations to make self-help efforts 
to develop goods that are salable on the Japanese market. 
  Commenting on the "reduction of Japan's current account 
surplus to about 2 percent of GDP," the centerpiece of the 
Keizai Doyukai's proposal to the Japanese Government, Keizai 
Doyukai President Masaru Hayami says: "This year, Japan's 
current account surplus is 2.8 percent of its GDP, a decrease of 
0.3 percentage points from a year earlier. If this trend 
continues every year, the target figure could be met." 
Regarding the action program on bridging price differentials 
between Japan and other nations, the president says, the action 
program and timetable should be worked out to cut in half the 
gap between the exchange rate and purchasing power parity. He 
urges the U.S. Government to stabilize the exchange rate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

