<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Names New Panels To Study Deregulation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003041894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 10 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1003041894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 10 March Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The government on 9 March decided to set up 
additional working groups under the Administrative Reform 
Promotion Headquarters (headed by Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa) and to have them come up with, by the end of June, 
additional deregulation measures primarily in the areas of 
market-access barriers and import controls. Keiretsu dealings 
and other commercial practices which have come under attack by 
other countries are also expected to become the subjects of 
study by these groups. 
  The U.S. Government has asked the Japanese Government to 
move 
up the target for finalizing the deregulation enforcement 
five-year plan, which is now set for completion by March 1995, 
to mid-July, when the summit of industrialized nations (Naples 
summit) will be held. The government is due to discuss measures 
including this point at the 10 March cabinet ministers meeting 
on foreign economic issues. 
  The government held a ministers meeting on 9 March to 
discuss 
issues concerning the Japanese-U.S. economic framework talks and 
agreed that the market-liberalization measures now under study 
should be finalized in two groups -- the first measures by the 
end of March and the second measures by the time of the summit 
in July. 
  During a news conference on the evening of the same day, 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura said that the 
government will set up immediately, in addition to the existing 
deregulation working group on land and housing issues, a similar 
working group on the information communications sector and 
another on the distribution sector by the end of the month. 
These working groups will deal with issues related to market 
access and regulations governing imports, and they will study 
deregulation measures that would lead to the promotion of 
imports. 
  Meanwhile, in relation to this question, a government source 
on the same evening noted, "Even among cabinet members, views 
are emerging on the need to review Japan's commercial practices." 
  According to the Foreign Ministry, the United States has 
requested Japan to add to the "deregulation enforcement plan" 
deregulation measures concerning the distribution sector as well 
as measures for improving the transferability of land. The 
United States has also asked about the schedule for finalizing 
the plan, and it noted with respect to the deadline for 
implementing the plan, "We hope that Japan will not try to 
adhere to the implementation deadline of five years but rather 
will facilitate its implementation before that." 

</TEXT>

