<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   BOJ Still Cautious About Economic Conditions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403055994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0403055994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Bank of Japan [BOJ] remains cautious about 
current economic conditions given in the short-term announcement 
released on 1 March. The BOJ considers it an encouraging 
indication that there are signs the economy has hit bottom, as 
seen in increased shipments of electric appliances. But 
Kagehide Kaku, chief of the BOJ Research and Statistics 
Department, said: "It is difficult to predict precisely when 
the economic recovery will start." This means that should the 
economy deteriorate further because of worsened labor conditions 
and the yen's sharp appreciation, the BOJ intends to take prompt 
measures to induce lower short-term rates. 
  The reason why the BOJ is cautious about the economic future 
is because while there are some favorable economic factors like 
increased investments in equipment and expansion of public works 
projects, there are also unfavorable factors such as those seen 
in unemployment problems and the yen's appreciation. In other 
words, the BOJ thinks: "The current situation is a mixture of 
contrasting factors." The BOJ is particularly nervous about the 
trend of high yen value and labor conditions. The fact that the 
private sector's investment in plants and equipment are not 
expected to grow even in 1994 is also contributing to its 
thinking that "no clear indications have been identified to 
confirm the economic recovery." 
  Meanwhile, the financial market is rather optimistic 
compared 
with the BOJ, believing: "The economy is recovering after 
having hit bottom." The BOJ wants to watch how current 
long-term interest rates will increase in the future. Should 
the increase be too sharp, thus bringing about a negative impact 
on the recovery, it will act to further ease the monetary market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

