<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   JNP Names Matsuoka New Secretary General </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003032994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1003032994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 8 March, the Japan New Party [JNP] decided on 
five new party executives, including Sumio Matsuoka, who will 
succeed Satoshi Arai as secretary general. Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa (JNP representative), who had been entrusted 
with the selection of the new officials, announced the lineup at 
a meeting of JNP Diet members of both houses on the morning of 
the same day and won their approval. Because dissatisfaction 
with the former executive board has been expressed within the 
party, claiming that "the party's management and personnel 
affairs are influenced by the intention of the secretariat," the 
possibility of changing executives has been studied. The five 
new executives will soon select members of the standing 
executive committee, which is a decision-making body second only 
to the party convention. 
  The new executives are: Kunitaro Takeda, (who will remain 
as) acting secretary general; Masuo Matsuoka, secretary general; 
Eiji Nagai and Muneaki Samejima, deputy secretary general; and 
Hirotaro Yamazaki, chairman of the general committee of Diet 
members of both houses. 

</TEXT>

