<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pact on Legal Cooperation Signed With Australia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0903102894 Vientiane KPL in English 0909 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0903102894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane KPL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vientiane, March 9 (KPL) -- The Ministry of Justice 
of Lao PDR [People's Democratic Republic] and the Australian 
Attorney General's Department signed on 8 March 1994 a 
memorandum of understanding on cooperation in legal affairs, 
according to a press release by the Australian embassy here. 
  The document was signed by Somlit Chanthachak, deputy 
minister of justice, and Alan Rose, secretary of the Australian 
Attorney General's Department. It spelled out both sides' 
intention to consolidate their bilateral relations and 
cooperation. Under the agreement Australia will provide 
assistance to the school of laws of the Ministry of Justice. 
  On the same occasion, Alan Rose presented law texts on 
different subjects, including environmental protection, 
business, commerce and others to the Lao Ministry of Justice. 
  Justice Minister Kham-ouan Boupha and Australian Ambassador 
to Laos Michael Mann witnessed the signing of this document. 
  While in Laos, Alan Rose held talks with a number of Lao 
ministers, with an emphasis on possibilities of cooperation in 
legal affairs between the two countries. He left here yesterday 
ending his five-day working visit to Laos. He also spent a short 
visit to Luang Prabang Province. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

