<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   7, 8 March U.S.-ROK `War' Exercises Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003043194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0418 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 10 (KCNA) -- The U.S. imperialists 
on March 8 brought two Okinawa-based KC-135 tanker planes to the 
sky above South Korea to stage a war exercise against the 
northern half of Korea, refueling in mid air at night some 
twenty fighter-bombers and assault planes including F-16s and 
A-10s belonging to the U.S. Air Force present in South Korea, 
according to military sources. 
  On the same day, some 10 large cargo planes based in the 
U.S. 
mainland and the Pacific airlifted a large aggression force and 
combat equipment to the U.S. Air Force bases in Osan and Kunsan. 
And an Okinawa-based RC-135 strategic reconnaissance plane, 
flying above the area of the military demarcation line, 
committed photographing and electronic reconnaissance on the 
strategic in- depth areas of the North. 
  On March 7, puppet army ground units ran amok in a war 
exercise in Yonchon and Paju counties, firing shells and 
large-calibre machinegun bullets. 

</TEXT>

