<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Groups Decry South Nuclear Development </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0903234994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1514 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0903234994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["`South Korea's Nuclear Arms Development Must Be Checked'" </F>
-- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 9 (KCNA) -- The world public is 
demanding a stop to the nuclear arms development by the South 
Korean authorities. 
  The Zimbabwe-Korea Solidarity and Friendship Association in 
a 
statement February 24 noted that the South Korean authorities 
under the aegis of the United States worked out a policy of 
developing nuclear weapons and introduced heavy water reactors 
from the 1970s and now have stockpiled plutonium enough to make 
hundreds of nuclear bombs and are using them in developing 
nuclear weapons. 
  The statement stressed that the South Korean authorities 
must 
immediately renounce the policy of nuclear arms development that 
gravely jeopardizes the Korean nation's right to existence and 
peace and security in Northeast Asia, and must remove the 
already stockpiled plutonium and remove the heavy water reactors 
or replace them aith light water reactors. 
  The Indian paper TAMAKA DARBAR said it is no secret that 
South Korea now is possessed of all basic indices of nuclear 
armament such as the technology of nuclear development, 
operation of reactors, extraction of nuclear materials, 
manufacture of nuclear bombs, nuclear testing, possession of 
means of nuclear delivery and the established system of war by 
nuclear weapons. 
  The Nepalese paper HINDU DAINIK wrote that nuclear threat on 
the Korean peninsula actually comes from South Korea, saying the 
world recognizes North Korea's sincere efforts for the 
denuclearization of the Korean peninsula. 
  Jose Fanequico, executive secretary of the Mozambican 
Committee for Friendship With the People of the Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea, in a statement urged that the United 
States and the International Atomic Energy Agency should discard 
their double- standard policy and check South Korea's nuclear 
arms development that threatens peace and security in Asia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

