<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Villages Change Since Rural Theses Published </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0803153094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1511 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0803153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Modern Village Thriving Under Tender Care" -- KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 8 (KCNA) -- Full-fledged 
preparations for farming are under way in Unjong-ri following 
the 30th anniversary of the publication of the socialist rural 
theses (February 25, 1964). The repair and readjustment of farm 
machines has been completed and the reservoirs are filled with 
water. Substantial preparations for sowing have been made, and 
carrying composts to paddy and non-paddy fields and carpeting 
fields with humus soil have entered the finishing stage. 
  Unjong-ri is 30 kilometres away from the seat of Pongsan 
County, North Hwanghae Province, in the central west of Korea. 
The village surrounded with high and low mountains looks like a 
picture. It has turned into a modern socialist village good to 
live and work in under the deep care of the dear leader Comrade 
Kim Chong-il. 
  He visited it (then Tanghyon-ri, Sohung County) in winter 30 
odd years ago and told by farmers there that they had eked out a 
hand-to-mouth existence with mountain-side tilling and 
charcoal-making before the liberation of the country, he 
unfolded a bright prospect for rural construction. He said the 
farmers in the mountain areas must turn the mountains to 
advantage, if they were to be well off and that they must 
create orchards on sunny hillside, raise silkworms, and actively 
tap mountain resources to improve their living standard. Saying 
they should rezone small plots into paddy fields and build many 
modern houses, he indicated a concrete orientation and ways. 
  This place has changed beyond recognition since then. 
Two-and three-storied modern houses for hundreds of families, a 
nursery, a kindergarten, schools, a hospital and public welfare 
facilities are standing in rows along the scenic Tanghyon River. 
Thirty five hectares of paddy fields fit for tillage by 
machines have taken shape in the place where not a plot of paddy 
field could be seen before liberation. And nearly 200 hectares 
of orchards and more than 700 hectares of forests of economic 
value have been created. Tractors, rice-transplanting machines, 
rice plucking machines and other farm machines have relieved the 
agricultural working people from toil. 
  Agricultural production has grown every year, the output of 
grain jumping 3.6 times, meat 4.6 times, fruits 7.6 times and 
vegetables 21 times as against 30 years ago. 
  Tanghyon-ri was renamed Unjong (benevolence)-ri in October 
1981 to hand down through generations the deep loving care shown 
by the dear leader for the farmers there. 
  Such change as in Unjong-ri can be seen everywhere in Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5723 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas047_l_94002" </HT>


