<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pioneer, U.S. Lab To Work on Digital CATV </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003081894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0723 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Pioneer Electronic Corp. 
said Thursday [10 March] it has agreed with Cable Television 
Laboratories Inc. (Cablelabs) of the United States to develop 
digital signal transmission technology for North American cable 
television systems. The agreement calls for the two parties to 
join hands in developing and standardizing a technique called 
16VSB -- vestigal sideband -- which is suitable for high volume 
data transmission, the leading audiovisual equipment maker said 
in a press release. 
  Digital signal transmission technology is viewed as a key 
element that will play a part in the next-generation digital 
CATV network, it said. 
  Under the agreement, Pioneer will be responsible for 
development of transmission technology and special 
semiconductors, and Cablelabs will provide technical facilities 
and testing assistance, the company said. Pioneer said it 
expects results by the spring of 1995. 
  Cablelabs is a research and development consortium of Cable 
Television System Operators representing more than 85 percent of 
cable subscribers in the U.S. 
  The U.S. cable television industry is moving forward in 
building a next-generation CATV system for the so-called 
"Information Superhighway" championed by the administration of 
President Bill Clinton. 

</TEXT>

