<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plaintiffs File Appeal Over U.S. Base Flights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903130494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1240 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Naha, March 9 KYODO -- A group of 907 plaintiffs 
filed an appeal against the state with the Fukuoka High Court on 
Wednesday [9 March], protesting a lower court's rejection of 
their plea to suspend U.S. military flights from the Kadena Air 
Base in Okinawa Prefecture due to noise pollution. Their 
lawyers said their clients have also criticized the ruling of 
the Okinawa branch of the Naha District Court for failing to 
reflect an appropriate amount of compensation. 
  On February 24, the branch court ordered the state to pay a 
total of 807.45 million yen to 768 residents around the U.S. 
Kadena Air Base in compensation for noise pollution. 
  The court rejected the suit by the other 139 plaintiffs on 
the grounds that they did not suffer the same level of 
inconvenience. The ruling rejected demands for a halt to night 
flights at the base in line with a Supreme Court decision in 
February last year involving Yokota Air Base in Tokyo and Atsugi 
Air Base in Kanagawa Prefecture. 
  The group of 907 residents demanded a halt to flights to and 
from the Kadena base between 7 P.M. and 7 A.M., 1.15 million 
yen each in damages for noise-related suffering and compensation 
for future annoyance until a night flight ban is imposed. 
  Kadena Air Base is under the control of the 18th Tactical 
Fighter Wing and is considered a key base of the U.S. Air Force 
in East Asia. 

</TEXT>

