<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Secretary of State Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Holds Meeting With Hata </H4>
<F P=102> OW1003111794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1058 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher asked Thursday [10 March] for Japan's support 
if the issue of North Korea's suspected nuclear development 
program is brought to the U.N. Security Council for discussion, 
Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said. Christopher made the 
call in talks with Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata in reference to 
North Korea's suspected nuclear development program and ongoing 
inspections of its seven declared nuclear facilities, the 
officials said. 
  Hata told Christopher that Japan will fulfill its role as a 
member of the United Nations in such a case, and gave high marks 
to Washington's "tenacious" negotiations with Pyongyang, they 
said. The two men agreed in the meantime to continue 
cooperation to solve problems regarding North Korea's alleged 
nuclear weapons program, the officials said. 
  North Korea announced a year ago that it would withdraw from 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT) but suspended the 
decision after negotiations with the United States. 
  Late last month, Pyongyang said it will allow inspections by 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) of seven of its 
nuclear facilities and the IAEA inspectors entered Pyongyang on 
March 1. 
  Washington and Pyongyang are scheduled to hold a third round 
of high-level talks beginning March 21 in Geneva on the 
condition that North Korea comply with a four-point accord that 
includes successful completion of the nuclear inspections. 
  Christopher arrived in Tokyo from Australia on Wednesday on 
the second leg of a three-nation tour which also takes him to 
China on Friday. 
  The secretary of state urged Japanese support in pushing 
China's leadership to improve its human rights record, the 
officials said. Christopher told Hata that the U.S. considers 
improvement in China's human rights record as an important 
condition to extend most-favored-nation (MFN) trade status to 
Beijing. 
  Hata noted that Japan has been urging China to improve its 
human rights record. 
  Christopher and Hata both expressed concern over the recent 
emergence of ultranationalists in Russia, the officials said. 
  Christopher said he does not think a spy scandal involving a 
high-ranking CIA official will affect U.S.-Russian ties in the 
long term, they said. He also said Washington welcomes Moscow's 
initiative in the conflicts in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  On Friday, Christopher and Undersecretary of Defense Frank 
Wisner will hold "two-plus-two" security talks with Hata and 
Defense Agency chief Kazuo Aichi. 
  Christopher is scheduled to deliver a speech before Japanese 
business leaders later the same day. 

</TEXT>

