<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Secretary of State Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Talks With Cambodia's Ranariddh </H4>
<F P=102> OW1003060994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0539 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003060994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Cambodian First Prime 
Minister Norodom Ranariddh said Thursday [10 March] the 
government remains open to a dialogue with the Khmer Rouge, but 
not "negotiations" that would imply further concessions to the 
guerrilla group. 
  "Our doors are still open," Ranariddh told reporters after 
he 
and Second Prime Minister Hun Sen held talks with U.S. Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher. "No negotiations, but we are ready 
to talk," Ranariddh said, adding that the Khmer Rouge "have to 
be more reasonable." 
  Ranariddh and Hun Sen arrived in Tokyo on Wednesday to 
attend 
a two-day international conference on aid to Cambodia which 
began Thursday. In his address to the conference, Ranariddh 
urged the international community "to help...solve the question 
of the Khmer Rouge as best it can" by seeing to it that the 
provisions of the October 1991 Paris peace agreements on 
Cambodia are strictly implemented. 
  In a barb clearly aimed at neighboring Thailand, which has 
been repeatedly accused by the Cambodian Government of allowing 
the Khmer Rouge sanctuary across the border, Ranariddh urged all 
signatories of the Paris agreements to fully respect them. 
  Ranariddh's father King Norodom Sihanouk, in a message read 
out at the conference, held out an olive branch to the Khmer 
Rouge, saying that "the door remains open to the most moderate 
elements and I do not despair of their future integration, there 
being an irresistible spirit towards total national 
reconciliation." 
  Christopher warned in his address that considering that the 
Khmer Rouge has not yet disarmed, "the future of democracy in 
Cambodia can hardly be taken for granted." 

</TEXT>

