<H3> <TI>   Cambodia's Hun Sen Asks for SDF Expertise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003091294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0849 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003091294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Cambodia's Second Premier 
Hun Sen told former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe on Thursday 
[10 March] his country hopes to borrow expertise from Japan's 
Self-Defense Forces (SDF) to train retired Cambodian soldiers in 
technical skills. He urged Watanabe to use his political 
influence to help Cambodia get SDF assistance, Japanese 
officials said. 
  Watanabe, however, said it would be difficult to realize 
such 
a project as the Japanese Constitution allows SDF dispatch 
abroad only for United Nations peacekeeping operations. 
  Hun Sen suggested the experts could also be retired SDF 
personnel, the officials added. 
  Hun Sen and his co-premier Norodom Ranariddh, who are 
currently in Japan to attend an international conference on 
assistance for Cambodia's reconstruction, met Watanabe at a 
Tokyo hotel. 

</TEXT>

