<H3> <TI>   Official: DPRK May Possess Long-Range Missile </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003102794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1007 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Vice Defense Minister 
Shigeru Hatakeyama said Thursday [10 March] it is possible that 
North Korea has developed a long-range missile capable of 
hitting targets more than 2,000 kilometers away. 
  "North Korea has placed stress on its military. Looking at 
the facts that it has developed the Nodong-1 through upgrading 
Scud missiles and has improved its technologies, we cannot 
totally deny that it may produce a further upgraded one," he 
said. 
  Hatakeyama, speaking at a news conference, discussed a 
report 
by the authoritative JANE'S DEFENSE WEEKLY that North Korea is 
developing two new ballistic missiles, one of which is capable 
of landing anywhere in Japan. Pyongyang last year test-fired 
the Nodong-1 ballistic missile with an estimated range of 1,000 
kilometers -- capable of striking Seoul and western parts of 
Japan. 
  Hatakeyama, however, said the Defense Agency has not 
independently confirmed the JANE's report. According to JANE's, 
U.S. intelligence satellites have detected a new "missile 
simulator," a hardware mock-up of a missile, at the Sanum Dong 
research facility in North Korea. 
  The weekly said the new two-stage missile has been given the 
provisional designation Taepo Dong-2 (TD-2) by U.S. 
intelligence. The mock-up was 32 meters long, comprising an 18 
by 2.4 meter diameter first stage and a 14 by 1.3 meter second 
stage rocket. 
  The TD-2's dimensions indicate the missile would have a 
range 
far greater than the 2,000 kilometers of the Taepo Dong-1 
(TD-1), also under development by North Korea, the magazine 
said. Jane's said U.S. officials also believe the missile has a 
much improved targeting capability and is possibly able to 
achieve a range of 3,500 kilometers, putting it in striking 
distance of Guam. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

