<H3> <TI>   French Trade Minister Comments on Super 301 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003113894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1109 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- French Trade Minister 
Gerard Longuet on Thursday [10 March] criticized Washington's 
retaliatory trade policy against Japan. The global community 
regards Japan's huge trade surplus as "a problem" for the world, 
but resorting to steps like Super 301 is an "overreaction," 
Longuet said. 
  Longuet made the remarks in his meeting with his Japanese 
counterpart Hiroshi Kumagai. 
  France and other European countries are against trade 
policies accompanied by sanctions, Longuet said. "Such a step 
is unlikely to solve problems on a long-term basis." 
  Kumagai said Japan will not leave unattended the soured 
economic ties with the United States following the breakdown of 
trade "framework" talks in February. 
  Longuet called for global economic cooperation with Japan in 
such fields as automobiles, aircraft and energy. He also 
proposed Japan and other Asian countries step up cooperation for 
industrial development. 
  Kumagai shared the view with the French trade minister, who 
arrived Tuesday for a visit lasting through Sunday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5742 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas047_a_94013" </HT>


