<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Thursday [10 March] expressed hope to visit France 
before this year's summit of the Group of Seven (G-7) major 
industrialized nations set for Naples in July, a Foreign 
Ministry official said. Hosokawa made the remark in a meeting 
with Gerard Longuet, the French trade and industry minister, at 
the prime minister's official residence Thursday [10 March]. 
  Longuet invited Hosokawa to France as early as possible, the 
official said. Hosokawa did not make clear when he wants to 
visit France, the official said. 
  Longuet was quoted as telling Hosokawa that France and Japan 
can cooperate in helping reconstruct Cambodia from years of 
civil strife and contribute to the international community 
together. 
  He also lauded Hosokawa's courage to institute national 
reforms, including the recently achieved political reform, the 
official said. 
  Longuet arrived in Tokyo on Wednesday for talks with 
Japanese 
Government and business leaders and to attend an international 
conference on assistance to Cambodia, which opened its two-day 
session at a Tokyo hotel Thursday. 

