<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Send Labor Minister to G-7 Job Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003074594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0714 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003074594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Japan will send only the 
labor minister from among cabinet members to the Group of Seven 
(G-7) "Jobs Summit" in Detroit on May 14-15, a top government 
spokesman said Thursday [10 March]. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told reporters 
the 
government has decided to send only Labor Minister Chikara 
Sakaguchi to the Detroit meeting as other ministers invited to 
the meeting are unable to go because of Diet business. "There 
is a perception that deliberation on the (fiscal 1994) budget is 
more important, so the government made a decision to have only 
the labor minister attend," Takemura said. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton has invited officials of the 
other G-7 major industrial countries -- Japan, Germany, Britain, 
France, Italy and Canada -- to the meeting to discuss ways to 
create new jobs. 
  From Japan, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii, International 
Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai and Economic 
Planning Agency Director General Manae Kubota were also invited 
to the meeting. 

</TEXT>

