<H3> <TI>   Domestic Rice Prices `Almost' Stop Rising </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903093494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0820 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Domestic rice prices in the 
free market almost stopped rising Wednesday [9 March] after a 
period of increases following a government decision to 
distribute state-controlled rice blended with foreign rice, a 
private rice market survey agency said. 
  The rice databank said 60 kilograms of "Koshihikari" rice 
produced in Niigata Prefecture were traded at between 53,200 yen 
and 53,600 yen in Tokyo and Osaka free markets, only 300 yen 
higher than a week before. 
  Although the price of "Kirara 397" in Hokkaido is still 
rising, rises in other brands have been shrinking, the 
Tokyo-based agency said. 
  A free rice market official in Osaka said most consumers who 
persist in eating domestic rice seemed to have purchased what 
they want prior to the distribution of government-controlled 
rice, which will be blended with foreign rice to counter the 
domestic crop shortfall in 1993. 

</TEXT>

