<H3> <TI>   Government To Supply 30,000 Tons More of Rice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003145394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1410 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- The Food Agency said 
Thursday [10 March] an additional 30,000 tons of rice, harvested 
in Japan, will be supplied to the market between this month and 
June as an emergency measure to meet a shortage. 
  The 30,000 tons, equivalent to two days' national 
consumption, are part of the agency's prefectural branch stocks, 
agency officials said. However, it is up to prefectural 
governments to determine when to put the extra rice on the 
market, the officials said. 
  The shortage is caused partly by delayed imports of foreign 
rice, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

