<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cold Weather `Likely' To Affect Rice Crops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003093994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0739 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Cold weather is likely to 
hit northern and eastern Japan from April to September, the 
months for growing rice, the Meteorological Agency said in its 
long-term forecast on Thursday [10 March]. 
  Last year's cold weather brought about a poor harvest of 
rice 
crops throughout Japan, forcing the government to import rice 
from foreign producers as an emergency measure. 
  The northern and eastern regions of Japan are known as rice 
producing areas and officials said the expected cold weather for 
a second year in a row may possibly result in another poor 
harvest. 

</TEXT>

