<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daiwa Securities Head To Lead Brokerage Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0903032194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0257 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0903032194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 9 KYODO -- Daiwa Securities Co. 
Chairman Sadakane Doi was unofficially appointed Wednesday [9 
March] as the next chairman of the Japan Securities Dealers 
Association, association officials said. The appointment of 
Doi, 65, to the post will be officially determined on July 1 at 
a meeting of directors. 
  Masaru Aratani, 69 , a former deputy president of the Tokyo 
Stock Exchange, is currently chairman of the association. 
  This is the first time since the revelation of the series of 
stock scandals in 1991 that an official from one of the "big 
four" brokerage houses will head the securities industry 
organization. Before the stock scandals involving loss 
compensation by major brokerages to big customers were revealed, 
the big four -- Nomura Securities Co., Nikko Securities Co., 
Yamaichi Securities Co. as well as Daiwa -- customarily took 
turns to supply the association's chief. 
  The outcry against the malpractice forced the big four to 
take a back seat, but the prolonged securities business slump 
and intensifying competition led many smaller brokerages to call 
for leadership from the big players, according to the officials. 
  The officials said the association will ask the Finance 
Ministry to end its restriction on the association personnel, 
set in the wake of the scandals. The ministry has advised the 
association that its head should not double in the post and as 
chief of his own company. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

