<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Official on Regrouping of Cement Industry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003120394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0933 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- A top trade ministry 
official on Thursday [10 March] supported the accelerated 
regrouping of the cement industry in Japan. "Reorganization is 
an inevitable move facing the industry," said the official at 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, who declined 
to be named. 
  The comment followed a merger accord reached earlier in the 
day between Sumitomo Cement Co., the fourth biggest cement maker 
in Japan, and the eighth largest Osaka Cement Co., a move that 
will create the nation's second largest cement maker with a 
market share of about 18 percent. 
  The merger is expected to speed up the collapse of joint 
sales alliances formed among Japan's cement makers a decade ago. 
Of the five joint sales entities, two -- one led by Onoda 
Cement Co. and the other by Ube Industries Ltd. and Chichibu 
Cement Co. -- have already been dissolved. Another, led by 
Sumitomo Cement Co., will be disbanded by the end of this month. 
  The latest move by Sumitomo and Osaka would lead to 
extinction of one of the remaining two alliances -- the one led 
by Nihon Cement Co. -- because Osaka belongs to the group. 
  The alliances were established as an exception to the 
Antimonopoly Law under the MITI's strong administrative guidance 
as part of the cement industry's streamlining efforts. But the 
long recession in Japan has prompted business tie-ups beyond the 
framework of the original alliances. 
  Mergers could have more cost-cutting effects than under the 
alliances in which cement makers cooperated in such sales fields 
as unification of product brands and distribution systems, the 
MITI official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

