<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister on Team Spirit; N-S Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003085094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0842 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 10 (YONHAP) -- In case the inter-Korean 
working-level contacts fail to make any progress, it is only 
natural that the third round of high-level talks between 
Pyongyang and Washington will be suspended and that Team Spirit 
will be resumed, Prime Minister Yi Hoe-chang confirmed on 
Thursday. 
  Yi noted, in a meeting with journalists, that holding the 
third round of high-level talks and suspending "Team Spirit," 
the annual South Korean-U.S. joint military exercise, had been 
decided on condition that South and North Korea exchange special 
envoys. 
  Last month, Pyongyang told Washington it would allow 
unrestricted IAEA [International Atomic Energy Agency] access to 
seven declared facilities and accept Seoul's proposal to hold 
working-level talks on exchanging presidential envoys. 
  In return, Washington was to suspend this year's Team Spirit 
and conduct high-level talks with North Korea later this month. 
  "Given the North Korean attitude we saw at the working-level 
contacts until yesterday, I doubt if North Korea really intends 
to exchange special envoys with the South. Inter-Korean 
contacts, if they are only for show (to others), are 
meaningless," Yi said. 
  Yi avoided making any decisive remarks on whether Team 
Spirit 
would be held. 
  "I cannot affirm that because it is a subtle military 
problem. I think we'll have to watch the progress of the 
inter-Korean working- level contacts, expecting that Pyongyang's 
attitude will change at the sixth contact slated for Saturday 
[12 March]." 
  He said now is not the time to comment on whether 
international sanctions may be imposed on North Korea if the 
special envoy exchange is not realized. 
  On reports that International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
inspectors had found a damaged seal at the North Korean nuclear 
facilities, Yi said he was briefed on the results of the IAEA 
inspection. 
  "But that is a problem for the IAEA to cope with, anyway," 
he 
said. 

</TEXT>

